{"id":"1201.4086","submitter":"Jean-Pierre Demailly","authors":"Jean-Pierre Demailly (IF), Hoang Hiep Pham","title":"A sharp lower bound for the log canonical threshold","comments":"7 pages. Paper accepted in Acta Mathematica, this second version\n  includes proof corrections","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CV math.AG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this note, we prove a sharp lower bound for the log canonical threshold of\na plurisubharmonic function $\\varphi$ with an isolated singularity at $0$ in an\nopen subset of ${\\mathbb C}^n$. This threshold is defined as the supremum of\nconstants $c>0$ such that $e^{-2c\\varphi}$ is integrable on a neighborhood of\n$0$. We relate $c(\\varphi)$ with the intermediate multiplicity numbers\n$e_j(\\varphi)$, defined as the Lelong numbers of $(dd^c\\varphi)^j$ at $0$ (so\nthat in particular $e_0(\\varphi)=1$). Our main result is that\n$c(\\varphi)\\ge\\sum e_j(\\varphi)/e_{j+1}(\\varphi)$, $0\\le j\\le n-1$. This\ninequality is shown to be sharp; it simultaneously improves the classical\nresult $c(\\varphi)\\ge 1/e_1(\\varphi)$ due to Skoda, as well as the lower\nestimate $c(\\varphi)\\ge n/e_n(\\varphi)^{1/n}$ which has received crucial\napplications to birational geometry in recent years. The proof consists in a\nreduction to the toric case, i.e. singularities arising from monomial ideals.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 19 Jan 2012 15:38:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Feb 2014 15:14:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-02-17"}
